text: Everyone complaining it didn't happen in the book, let us point out the obvious: There are crows flying around, a house is flying, Tris is jumping off of buildings and disappearing through walls, her mother is there... Clearly, that means it's a SIMULATION. Which one it is is not clear, but the general consensus seems to point to either it being one of Jeanine's Fear Serum Sims [or several of them meshed together] or it's the nightmare Tris experiences when she remembers her parents and Will, OR it's the nightmare she wakes up from before she asks Four if she can stay with him and he tells her he'll fight off her nightmares with his bare hands, in Amity. text: Just to clear a few things up (No spoilers):  First off, the CGI. The CG is so bad in the trailer for one of two reasons. The first is that this is one of Tris' nightmares and they are trying to display that this is a dream by making the CG look fake. The second reason (unlikely) is that this whole scene you are seeing here, is purely made for advertising. Many movies have done this before, and it's kind-of smart because it shows what kind of action you'll be seeing in the movie, without actually seeing scenes from the movie.  Secondly, Tris' haircut. We're all freaking out for one of two reasons. The first is all the people who haven't read the book and think that they just did this because it was convenient. Tris did cut her hair at the begging of the story. The second is people are wondering why it's so short. I think that it's this short because it would be so stupid if Shailene walked around with a wig, when in reality, it would be pointless to wear a wig because the effort does not profit.  Lastly, people are wonder why Abnegation is blown up or this didn't happen in the story. Abnegation being wrecked is probably like metaphor for all her people being destroyed or this is just how Tris imagines it in her head. Again, this might just be for advertising reasons, but it doesn't really matter if Tris' nightmares are changed, I mean, come on guys.  Thanks for reading! I hope this clears a few things up!

text: ok lemme drop a bit of knowledge in this comments section. First of all, in the books Tris cuts her hair so regardless of whether her hair is short on the actress, that's what Veronica Roth (the author) had her do in the second book anyway so it's necessary. Her mother is already dead so this is a dream which means that the graphics/slow motion/dramatics were put there purposefully to indicate that it isn't real. Because this is a teaser trailer, even though this particular scene wasn't in the books, Tris does have insistent dreams of her mother in the books so obviously they're playing on not showing what's going to happen in the movie because Insurgent really lurches right in and if they show too much in the trailer it'll be a massive spoiler and they're also amplifying her pain from losing her mother whilst showing the newer and stronger version of herself she's become. So stop whingeing jfc.

text: Ugh I'm in a ranty mood.  Okay. Has anyone who says Divergent and The Hunger Games are the same read ALL SIX books? I have and everyone needs to calm down lol. Seriously.  **WARNING: THERE IS SOME MAJOR MAJOR SPOILER SHIZ DOWN BELOW AND IT WILL RUING THE ENTIRE EXPERIENCE IF YOU EVER EVER PLAN ON READING ANY OF THE BOOKS (especially at book three of Divergent)**  Dystopian books are IN. They're POPULAR! There's a ton of them everywhere you go so just because one came out first and they're both popular doesn't mean one is a knockoff.¬† "They both have female leads." Yes. It's also been happening a lot lately. Giving woman recognition and showing they can be strong too? Yeah that happens. What about the Legend series? If that gets huge will it be a copy too? "They both have hot boyfriends." Really? Katniss actually struggles with two boys and she doesn't know which she loves for a majority of the series. Tris gets the guy easily but they struggle at being a couple. "They're both special." Okay 1, they're the MAIN CHARACTER so they usually have an advantage. 2, Katniss is "special" because she rebelled with some berries (I love THG btw I'm not trashing it). Tris has a different mindset than most people which makes her a danger to the government which is trying to rule and control simpleminded people. "They both fight the government." Yeah well that can actually be a representation of the actual fights countries have with their government and people and how some feel that the government rules over us. OR it could be a situation that represents fighting against those who hold you back from who you want and need to be. "They are both split into groups." This is actually very common in any work of art. Book, movie, play, song, FANFICTION, etc. There is always a separation be it cliques in a high school or making twenty foot walls to divide a country. "They're both written by woman." Leave. "They both have the same plot." The Hunger Games book one is about Katniss surviving the games, well mainly. Book two is about Katniss surviving the games a second time along with Peeta again because the government is trying to kill her off. Book three is about how she was rescued by fugitives and now they need to overthrow their corrupt government, or at least President Snow, to save many lives and fix Panem (North America). Divergent book one is Tris trying to make it through the tough initiation of her new faction and also hiding her specialness from the Erudite. And then saving her home faction. Book two is her trying to still hide her secret from the government and soon finding out how messed up it really is with the killing of the Divergents and blah blah blah fix things (again I love this series too no hate haha). Book three is about them finding out that their city is just an experiment among many others and that it is destined to destroy itself so they should probably fix it and save everyone's lives and Tobias isn't actually divergent and they need to save a a lot more than just their city because these experiment people are also pretty bad by letting people die and all of this stuff linking Tris's mom to the start of the Chicago experiment and yeah someone important dies shhhhhh. And then The Maze Runner series- nah I'm just kidding, but those books are amazing!!  I could go on and on but it seems pointless when people that don't know everything will just disregard what I say and jump on the idea of fighting to the death over books they haven't fully read and analyzed.

text: To all those snapping that this particular scene(which is most probably a Fear landscape/a nightmare,as mentioned bellow) is not in the book,and that that sole reason ruins the film. That's extremely unfair. Divergent retained the general essence and conception of the story we read and loved, and Insurgent will hopefully stand strong in the semantics of where divergent subjectively might have failed. But what we need to realise is,  The visual experience is very different from reading a story off paper. There's a different flow to it, a different dynamic. It is necessary to have adjustments, especially as long as it does n't mangle the integrity of its world. As Divergent fans, we will have remarks, but lets refrain from utterly unnecessary critical remarks. We should encourage this franchise. It is the fans who can often unintentionally bring about the downfall of film adaptions-granted some of them are dreadful, but they don't warrant quite as much disdain as they often get. Insurgent looks good, and I have hopes that it will be amazing, from this very bare minimal smidge of the film we've seen. Ôªø

text: cant freaking wait

Why do people always fail to understand that the written word and the big screen are two different mediums and that they do not always translate from one to the other 1:1? Whenever a book is adapted into a film some things will be changed, lost, or expanded upon along the way. Usually this is done to make a more cohesive film that still closely follows the most important parts of the book. Cohesive being the key word here. No one wants to sit through a four hour long movie that agonizes over every one of Tris' angsty thoughts. Just like no one wants to sit through a movie that'll bore them to death because what little real action happens throughout the series is given a cursory description (at best) between Tris' many attempts to martyr herself.  THAT SAID, this teaser was awesome and I hope the rest of this film is this visually engaging.

text: I really like the series, I've never read the  books however I enjoyed the movie and the subject matter is intriguing. ...intially the movie did remind of the Giver, however,  for the people that have negative things to say about the series, I mean,  when is the last time you wrote a book? Or had an independent idea? Maybe you should watch the Divergent series so  that your less judgemental....all stories are the same,  literally, they just change due to culture, social, economical necessity.  But to discredit the author,  and director by calling them copy cats is well pretty stupid in my opinion. Of course if you love literature, you will expect a lot from a film,  however when reading a book, you independently create, or imagine the setting,  to belive that A director, a cinematographer,  and set designers are going to literally incorporate your ideal is malarkey. APPRECIATE THE MOVIE FOR WHAT IT IS.  The movie,  and the book, are thought provoking, which to me signals that the author and director did their jobs.
